{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/retinal-detachment/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"06def8c4-72e1-5803-9856-4a5dc3251143","slug":"differential-diagnosis","fullItemName":"Differential diagnosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9221a029-0022-4684-867e-60d6d564440f --><h2>What else might it be?</h2><!-- end field 9221a029-0022-4684-867e-60d6d564440f -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 2360731e-8bf6-40a7-8ba0-7eed833313ff --><!-- begin field 74fab24f-66f3-4407-a84f-e20dfbb84667 --><ul><li><strong>Alternative causes of flashes include:</strong><ul><li>Posterior vitreous detachment (a simple collapse of the vitreous gel which increases the risk of developing retinal tears; may be part of the normal ageing process).</li><li>Migraine (visual aura may precede the headache; typically bright zigzag lines or spots with associated flashing coloured light sensations, occurring in the visual field of one or both eyes simultaneously and persisting for minutes or hours at a time). See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/migraine/\">Migraine</a> for more information.</li><li>Postural hypotension (typically presents with dizziness, lightheadedness, and blurred vision). See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/blackouts/\">Blackouts</a> for more information.</li><li>Optic nerve pathology, such as optic neuritis (may present with gradual visual loss often starting in the periphery, associated with flashes).</li><li>Transient ischaemic attack (amaurosis fugax presenting as transient visual loss like a curtain falling across the vision, and usually resolving within seconds to minutes). See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/stroke-tia/\">Stroke and TIA</a> for more information.</li><li>Choroidal tumours (rare; may cause spots of light travelling across the visual field and floaters).</li><li>Drugs such as chloroquine.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Alternative causes of floaters include:</strong><ul><li>Posterior vitreous detachment (a simple collapse of the vitreous gel which increases the risk of developing retinal tears; may be part of the normal ageing process).</li><li>Myopia (short-sightedness).</li><li>Vitreous haemorrhage (describes the leakage of blood or blood products from a retinal vessel around and into the vitreous gel, for example due to diabetic retinopathy or trauma).</li><li>Uveitis (especially posterior; typically causes visual loss, photophobia, and floaters). See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/uveitis/\">Uveitis</a> for more information.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 74fab24f-66f3-4407-a84f-e20dfbb84667 --><!-- end item 2360731e-8bf6-40a7-8ba0-7eed833313ff -->","topic":{"id":"9be2cb0d-8648-5694-a09c-292ca1ced19e","topicId":"e3f75bdf-a207-4239-9931-367d38a9b7d6","topicName":"Retinal detachment","slug":"retinal-detachment","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2019","chapters":[{"id":"842ff08c-c002-50cd-bab2-348ba3e67be0","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"98f29b98-1286-5c16-a606-4cd90cc70465","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"873d5520-2d22-5b9d-bd04-6d9112dc82ee","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3b54abb3-d415-51e3-996b-1d6e3bcc3d3b","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"0aa87cea-a601-54db-9dcb-ec3117e7098a","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"dbe4b4fd-c326-5686-bd9a-71905fc13c76","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"9f38c5e9-5edd-56fa-a740-0d19004a69af","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5960233a-64c2-5a35-95ea-6a44ae788808","slug":"outcome-me